Visualization Control System Basic Tutorial ¶

VCS Allows scientists to produce highly customized plots. Everything can be precisely and logically controlled, without any guessing game

The CDAT software was developed by LLNL. This tutorial was written by Charles Doutriaux. This work was performed under the auspices of the U.S. Department of Energy by Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory under Contract DE-AC52-07NA27344.

This tutorial is a high level flight of VCS capabilities

We encourage you to also consult the VCS Principles Notebook and CDMS 101

Download the Jupyter Notebook

Setup Notebook ¶

Back To Top

First let's download some sample data

In [1]:
from __future__ import print_function
import requests
import os

for filename in ['ta_ncep_87-6-88-4.nc', 'clt.nc', 'sampleCurveGrid4.nc']:
    if not os.path.exists(filename):
        r = requests.get("https://cdat.llnl.gov/cdat/sample_data/{}".format(filename), stream=True)
        with open(filename,"wb") as f:
            for chunk in r.iter_content(chunk_size=1024):
                if chunk:  # filter local_filename keep-alive new chunks
                    f.write(chunk)

Opening Data Files ¶

Back To Top

First we will open one of our demo files, this is done via the cdms2 module

In [2]:
import cdms2

f = cdms2.open("ta_ncep_87-6-88-4.nc")

First plot ¶

Back To Top

Let's visualize this variable, for this we will need the vcs module. we will also need a vcs canvas

In [5]:
import vcs
canvas = vcs.init(bg=True)  # Plot in background mode
canvas.plot(f["ta"])
Out[5]:

Subsetting Data¶

Back To Top

In the above plot we used all the variable dimensions and therefore got a boxfill. You can load and use a subset of the dimensions. Notice how we can use either actual dimension value or indices (via slice)

In [6]:
data = f["ta"](longitude=-90, latitude=40, level=500, time=slice(0,1))
print(data)

[[[[263.4303]]]]

In the previous example we fixed all dimensions and therefore got a single value. Let's subset longitude to a range rather than a single value and plot it

In [7]:
data = f["ta"](longitude=(0,180), latitude=40, level=500, time=slice(0,1), squeeze=1)  # The squeeze eliminates dimensions of length 1
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(data)
Out[7]:

Using isolines¶

Back To Top

Now if we want an isoline rahter than the default boxfill, we will need to to create the associated graphic method:

In [8]:
isoline = vcs.createisoline()
data = f("ta")
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(data, isoline)
Out[8]:

Cross sections¶

Back To Top

Let's plot a cross section of the data

In [9]:
canvas.clear()
data = f["ta"](longitude=-90, latitude=(-90,90), level=(1000,100), time=slice(0,1), squeeze=1)
canvas.plot(data, isoline)
Out[9]:

We can also colorize the isoline if we want. And turn on labels

In [10]:
levels = vcs.mkscale(*vcs.minmax(data))
colors = vcs.getcolors(levels)
isoline.levels = levels
isoline.linecolors = colors
isoline.label = True
isoline.textcolors= colors
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(data, isoline)
Out[10]:

Easy Plot Tweaks¶

Back To Top

We can also control the dimensions "range" on the plot via the graphic method. Or tweak the axes scale or change the default labels

In [11]:
data = f["ta"](longitude=-90, time=slice(0,1), squeeze=1)
# North pole on the left
isoline.datawc_x1 = 90
isoline.datawc_x2 = -90
isoline.datawc_y1 = 3  # log10(1000)
isoline.datawc_y2 = 2.3  # log10(200)
isoline.yaxisconvert = "log10"
isoline.yticlabels1 = {1000:"1000", 800:"800", 500: "500", 20:"20"}
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(data, isoline)
Out[11]:

Overlays¶

Back To Top

Now let's overlay another variable, since it has different values we will create a separate isoline graphics method

In [12]:
f2 = cdms2.open("clt.nc")
u = f2("u", longitude=-90., time=slice(0,1), squeeze=1)  # First time slice
iso2 = vcs.createisoline(source=isoline)  # Essentilly makes a copy
levels = vcs.mkscale(*vcs.minmax(u))
iso2.levels = levels
colors = ["blue",]  # blue lines
iso2.linecolors = colors
iso2.textcolors = colors
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(data, isoline)
canvas.plot(u, iso2)
Out[12]:

Manipulating Variables¶

Back To Top

Manipulating variables is easy, let's plot the temperature in Farenheight rather than Kelvin

In [13]:
ta_f = (f["ta"]-273.16)*9/5+32
ta_f.info()
ta_f.units = r"$^o$F"
ta_f.title = r"Air Temperature ($^o$F)"
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(ta_f)

One can also compose variables together

In [14]:
u = f2("u")
v = f2("v")
speed = cdms2.MV2.sqrt(u**2 + v**2)
speed.id = "Wind Speed"
speed.units = "m/s"
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(speed)
Out[14]:

Averaging ¶

Back To Top

Using the genutil module we can also easily average

In [15]:
import genutil, cdutil
data = f("ta", time=slice(0,5))
ta_avg = genutil.averager(data, axis='t')
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(ta_avg)
Out[15]:

We can also remove the zonal mean by averaging over longitude

In [16]:
ta = f("ta")
ta_zm = genutil.averager(f("ta"), axis="x")
print(ta_zm.shape)

In order to subtract it from ta, We need to put the missing longitude on ta_zm, e.g "grow" it back to 4D.

In [17]:
ta, ta_zm = genutil.grower(ta, ta_zm)
print(ta_zm.shape)
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(ta-ta_zm)
Out[17]:

We can do a simple time difference (last - first time point)

In [18]:
diff = ta[-1] - ta[0]
diff.shape
Out[18]:
(17, 73, 144)

Or an offset by one day at all points

In [19]:
offset = ta[1:] - ta[:-1]
offset.shape
Out[19]:
(10, 17, 73, 144)

Note that the other axes are preserved

Other graphic methods¶

Now we will move on to the topic of controlling the graphics output. So far, we have usually allowed VCS to chose the defaults.

Isofill¶

Back To Top

Beside the default boxfill, we have already seen one can plot data using isoline. Other available plot types are: isolfill

In [21]:
ta = f("ta", longitude=(-180, 0), latitude=(0,90), level=500, squeeze=1)
gm = vcs.createisofill()
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(ta, gm)
Out[21]:

Vectors ¶

Back To Top

vector (requires 2 variables)

In [22]:
u = f2("u", longitude=(-180, 0), latitude=(0,90), squeeze=1)
v = f2("v", longitude=(-180, 0), latitude=(0,90), squeeze=1)
gm = vcs.createvector()
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(u, v, gm)
Out[22]:

Streamlines ¶

Back To Top

streamlines (also requires 2 variables)

In [23]:
gm = vcs.createstreamline()
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(u,v, gm)
Out[23]:

Meshfill ¶

Back to Top

If your file is CF compliant, VCS can plot generic grids out of the box

In [24]:
f3 = cdms2.open("sampleCurveGrid4.nc")
curv = f3("sample")

m = vcs.createmeshfill()

canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(curv, m)
Out[24]:

Projections ¶

Back To Top

One can also alternate the projection

In [25]:
proj = vcs.createprojection()
proj.type = "lambert"
proj.standardparallel1 = 0
proj.standardparallel2 = 89
gm = vcs.createboxfill()
gm.projection = proj
canvas.clear()
canvas.plot(ta, gm)
Out[25]:
